Windsock east of and close to pad, trees south and buildings NE of pad.  Pad seems to be slowly sinking down on the west end.  Lights are high and close to pad.

Ongoing construction at the seawall to the west of the pad which will eventually effect the street to the north of the pad.  (est June '15-December '16).  

Also, from June 1, 2015 thru July 2016, a 174' lighted tower crane with a 230' arm will be located over the main hospital building.  Rises approximately 40' over the highest antenna on the hospital.  Should not affect operations at the helipad as long as the main hospital is not overflown.

column45:
Oak Hill Hospital is going to be constructing a 3rd and 4th floor on top of their new North Tower building.  Construction starts immediately and will last for approximately a year and a half (till Oct of '16)

There will be a portable 200’ crane operating north of the North Tower along its entire length (see attachment).  This crane will ostensibly be lit at night and is flagged.  We are also asking the construction crews to lower it to the level of the top of the building at night.  None of the construction should directly affect helicopter operations.

However, overflight over the entire construction area should be avoided and approaches and departures made from North west through South as per the attached diagram.

column59:
Interfacility Flights:
Communications Centers for inbound helicopters must provide telephonic notification to BHSP’s Security Department as soon as possible, but no later than 20 minutes prior to ETA using the below phone number.  If a stretcher is needed, Security should be informed at this time:

Security:  (727) 893-6144

Scene Calls:
For scene calls inbound to BHSP, in addition to the Security Department notification above,  notify the ED with aircraft ETA and any initial patient information at the following phone number:

Emergency Department:   (727) 553-7785

In addition, if the helicopter does not have the ability to communicate directly with the ED on the Pinellas Co. Med-8 800 MHz frequency, detailed patient information shall be relayed telephonically to the ED using the above phone number.

Please provide updates to the same departments if there is a significant change in the helicopter’s ETA.

column59: Formerly just "Shands Gainesville". North pad designated as "North Tower" and the Southern pad is the "South Tower" (The pin in the photo is on the North Tower). Patient room number will determine which pad (Tower) will be used. If aircraft is to remain on either pad it must shut down. Pilot must stay with the aircraft and give ShandsCair Operations a way to contact him/her while on the pad (this so he/she can be alerted to clear the pad for another inbound aircraft). Crews are advised to strictly adhere to the "Helicopter Pad Utilization Policy" for this hospital; arrival and departure radio calls (both on the Gainesville City UNICOM 123.025 and ShandsCair Operations) are mandated (the hospital is also within Gainesville Regional's airspace).  Contact ShandsCair for details.  Noise abatement area to South and West (Univ of Fl Vet Center).   Also check for TFRs at Univ of Fl Stadium.

Bremen, GA. 30110.  But, if viewed on Google Earth, the satellite view has not been updated with the building.  Please note there are perimeter light poles surrounding building.  I've visualized this area personally, and it is of sufficient size and free of obstacles other than the light poles which should not impede arrival and/or departure.)

Because of noise sensitive areas to west and north of hospital, APPROACH / DEPT PATHS  are NORTH  335 to 353 degrees or 027 to 060 degrees.   To the SOUTH 179 to 187 degrees.   PLEASE SEE ATTACHED PICTURE with approach / departure paths.

     3)   Prior to Lift

MEDCOM will notify security.
Call Memorial Med Flight (866-939-5317) with ETA as well as security.

We are pleased to announce that Norton Audubon Hospital helipad is now open!
 
Our security team will assist crews to their destination and back to the aircraft.
 
Pilots will have control of the helipad lights with 123.025 (3 clicks for pad lights, 5 for white walkway lights).
 
If you have any questions, concerns, suggestions, or need follow-up on anything, please feel free to contact me!
 
Please share the information above!
 
Semper Salus!
 
Renee Cecil, MSN, RN, CEN, CCCC, SANE, NREMT

column59: Rosecrans Memorial Airport is a large general aviation / military joint-use airport located 3 miles northwest of St. Joseph and 35 miles north of Kansas City. There are a variety of hotels within a 5- to 8-mile radius and rental cars can be obtained from the fixed base operator (FBO), Express Flight Inc. (EFI) or direct from the car companies. EFI also has a courtesy car available. Rosecrans Memorial Airport is open to the public 24/7, 365 days a year.  Tower is open 8 a.m. to 6 p.m. each day.

They block off the road normally and there are often numerous bystanders in the road and at the many stores on the east side of the road. There are trees to the south and power lines on ALL sides of the LZ. Best approach is from the South if possible and takeoff N or S. Landing area is somewhat sloped and uneven. It may be necessary to hover around to find the best spot to sit down. Again, terrible LZ but workable.

column46: From NIP SSW approach.
column59:
Helicopter Approach and Departure Procedures:
Note: maximum gross weight limitation of Helipad 1 and 2 are 10,000lbs and Helipad 3 is 11,000lbs
Contact Charlotte Approach on 120.05 when 20 to 25 miles out from our main hospital.
Notify Approach that you are inbound to Carolinas Medical Center and obtain clearance into Class B Airspace prior to penetrating the 7 NM arc around the Charlotte VOR (115.0).
Contact MedCenter Air Dispatch (Flight Watch) on primary 155.325 - PL 10 (91.5) or secondary 123.025.
Recommend 1500' - 1800' MSL for altitude.
Fly to a point just south of the skyscrapers of Charlotte (approximately 1/4 mile). Fly over top of the large hotel next to the Interstate 277.
Contact MedCenter Air Flight Watch and report "North IP for Pad?"
Follow the four-lane road (Kings Drive) southwest leading from the interstate area towards Carolinas Medical Center. When near the hospital at 500' AGL, make the turn toward Pad 1, 2 or 3.
Avoid flying any other route into or out of the hospital for noise abatement. Avoid low flight over residential areas near the hospital.
If the patient's condition is extremely critical, you can fly directly to the helipads. However, notify MedCenter Air Flight Watch or one of our crew members so a flight deviation report can be completed.
For departure from CMC helipad, contact MCA (Flight Watch) on primary 155.325 - PL 10 (91.5) or secondary 123.025 prior to start, then Charlotte ATC Tower while on the helipad on frequency 118.1. When communications with Charlotte Tower is established, advise the tower of your intentions, and request clearance to depart the pad and proceed. Do not depart the helipad without an ATC clearance, since the helipad is located inside Charlotte Class B Surface Area.

Additional LZ information - LZ Freq: Jefferson Fire / EMS-1.

Flight planning - direct to Watertown (KART) then to Chaumont. This will keep the aircraft feet dry the entire flight. Direct to the Pulaski Highway Dept LZ, KART then Chaumont. Again keeps the aircraft feet dry the entire flight. If wx allows you can hug the coast line on the southern portion o the lake then straight to KART. 
Be aware you may find snow-mobile traffic, trailers in, on or around the LZ in winter months. Apparently one of the local snowmobile clubs put out that the lot was a rally/node point for one of their rallies. If we are called you may see FD personnel herding/blocking this traffic. I would imagine it will be pretty clear by the time we arrive. The Chief has spoken to the club but he anticipates it to take a while for the word to get out to everyone.

column59:
Primary Fire Department  is McArthur Fire 2400
Vinton County Airport is in Swan Township Vinton County. Vinton County Airport operates on Unicom 122.8, has pilot activated runway and area lights.  Also, does have a windsock present.

column3: VC10 State Route 356 and Crow Road
column59:
Primary Fire Response is Zaleski Fire 2600
Landing Zone will be on State Route 356.  Surface will be a paved 2 lane State Highway.  There are Power Lines Immediately South of the Intersection however they are easily negligible when approaching from any other direction.

column3: VC11 State Route 32 and County Road 43C
column59:
Primary Fire Response is Hamden Fire 2300
Landing Zone will be on State Route 32. There are no obstructions present and landing may be placed in either section of highway. Note that this Vinton County Road 43C.  County Roads 43A and 43B also intersect with SR 32.

column3: VC12 State Route 327 and Eagle Mills
column59:
Primary Fire Response is Harrison Twp. Fire 2800
Landing Zone is at the Intersection of State Route 327 and Eagle Mills Road (Vinton County Road 17A) Area is heavily wooded but the intersection itself is clear of obstructions.

column3: VC13 Intersection of US 50 and SR 327
column59:
Primary Fire Response is Harrison Twp. Fire 280
Landing Zone will be at the intersection of US Highway 50 and State Route 327. Immediately North of the intersection is County Road 13B which also may be considered.  All areas are paved roadway.  No immediate obstructions.

column3: VC14 Intersection of SR 93 and SR 56
column59:
Primary Fire Department Area is McArthur Fire 2400
The intersection of State Route 93 and State Route 56 is a notorious intersection for severe motor vehicle crashes.  While there is no ideal location for a predetermined landing zone, the area warrants examination.  The most probable LZ would be directly on SR 56 just west of the intersection.  However, traffic congestion may cause for the actual LZ to be called by ground units.  Often patient will be transported by ground to EMS Station Helipad, (VC2).

column3: VC15 Intersection of SR 56 and Pumpkin Ridge Road
column59:
Primary Fire Department Area is McArthur Fire 2400
The intersection of State Route 56 and Vinton County Pumpkin Ridge Road.  This maybe also referred to as Orland. The LZ will be either on paved State Highway (SR 56) or Vinton County Road Pumpkin Ridge Road. There are several open fields in the area if Multiple LZs are needed.   There are no obstructions present.

Primary Fire Department  is McArthur Fire 2400	
The Vinton County EMS Helipad is located behind 31931 State Route 93 McArthur, Ohio.  This Helipad is concrete base measuring 30 ft. by 30 ft.  The Helipad is lit and has a wind sock.  No physical obstructions are near this landing zone. Site is vehicle accessible.

column3: VC3 Cross Creek or McArthur Fire Dept. Station #2
column59:
Primary Fire Department is McArthur Fire 2400
This LZ may be described as the Cross Creek LZ or Fire Station #2 .  It is a compacted/paved gravel landing zone with Windsock that is obstacle free.  The LZ measures 65 ft. by 65 ft. It is in Richland Township directly off US Highway 50.

column3: VC4 Hope School Lake Hope State Park
column59: Hope School LZ is located adajcent to Lake Hope State Park in the Zaleski State Forrest.  The LZ is actaully a paved parking lot at a tourist center. There is not a windsock or notable external lighting.  The Lot is 184 ft. by 58 ft. and is directly accesible by vehicle. There are power lines running West to North and trees to the south.  In the event of vehicles in lot, the field to the East is accessible as well.

Primary Fire Department is Hamden Fire 2300
South Elementary is located along State Route 93 in Hamden, Ohio.  The school provides several different areas for a safe landing.  The front parking lots are paved and lighted, however the parking lot lights may be a hazard.  There is a large grass area immediately to the Southeast of the structure that would provide a safe area for landing.  LZ will not be used during school sessions.

Primary Fire Department is Hamden Fire 2300
This LZ is at the intersection of State Route 160 and State Route 32. This intersection is open and is well known for serious MVC’s.  This is also an option for any Air Medical calls in the area.

Primary Fire Department is Wilkesville Fire 2500
Dynergy Electric Generation Plant is in Wilkesville Township. The facility includes a concrete Helipad measuring 95 ft. by 60 ft. This facility is located directly adjacent to State Route 160. Immediately to the North of the facility are several high-tension wires.  These should be easily avoidable with a southern approach. There is a windsock present however it is only approximately 8 feet from the ground.

Primary Fire Department  is Zaleski Fire 2600
This LZ is at the intersection of US Highway 50 and SR 278 in Madison Township.  The landing area will be on US Highway 50, preferbly just East of the intersection.  There are power lines in the immediate intersection and a gaurdrail along the South side of the highway. The landing surface will be a paved state highway.

Primary Fire Department is Zaleski Fire 2600
Landing zone will be on a large mowed grass yard.  Large trees do encompass the field, however are sufficient distance that they do not pose a hazard or obstruction.

column44: Is a 2 position heated metal rooftop located on top of a 12 story multicolored building in the Lawrenceville section of Pittsburgh.  The primary pad is 75 ft. by 75 ft. painted with a white cross and solid red H with yellow perimeter lighting. The Helipad Lighting is pilot controlled with 5mic clicks on 123.05.  There is an illuminated windsock atop the elevator entry on the northwest side of the helipad.  The 45 ft by 45 ft park position is located 115 feet west of the primary pad and is separated by a 16 foot wide walkway.  The Park position is labeled with a red P and has yellow perimeter lighting. The LZ itself is located approximately 2.5 miles ENE of downtown Pittsburgh south of the Allegheny River and beside Allegheny Cemetery.  Hazards:  The elevator shaft/access adjacent to the NW side of the helipad, ventilation units on the west side of the park position.  Coordinates are N 40 28.00 by W 079 57.16.
column45: The elevator shaft/access adjacent to the NW side of the helipad, ventilation units on the west side of the park position.
column46:
Primary approach:  Over the cemetery at 245 degrees and depart at 110 degrees.  Secondary approach 020 degrees and depart at 200 degrees.
All approaches must be made to the primary pad.  Park position may be available upon request. In the rare circumstance when an aircraft breaks down on the “H” position, approach and landing to the Park position is authorized “at the pilots discretion”. Aircraft may depart via the Primary or Park positions but may never overfly another parked aircraft. Unless safety of flight or patient condition dictates otherwise, pilots shall not commence approach or departure procedures without approval from STATCOM. Departures over the cemetery are recommended.    
If holding is required until pad is cleared to land, execute holding north of the helipad along the Allegheny River at 2000 feet or above.  Monitor 123.025 at all times.
**All Helipad landings use must be preceded by notification of STATCOM by telephone or radio when, at least, ten minutes out.
STATCOM radio frequency          155.265 (RPL15) pl 103.5
STATCOM telephone                     (412) 647-7828 or (800) 633-7828
column58: LZ is a 2 position, 60' x 200', heated metal rooftop helipad located on top of an 11 story beige & blue colored building with the word Children's painted on it. The transient position of the helipad is painted with a white cross & red H, amber colored approach & perimeter lighting.  There is an illuminated windsock & rotating red & white beacon atop an elevator shaft on the E side of the helipad. The park position is identified by the word park & blue colored perimeter lighting. The LZ itself is located approximately 2nm E of downtown Pittsburgh on a hill to the NW of Schenley Park & 1/4nm W of the Cathedral of Learning (a large tower with 3 amber colored lights on all 4 sides around the top of the tower). HAZARDS: The elevator shaft/access adjacent to the E side of the helipad, a smaller building adjacent park position on the N side of the helipad. PRIMARY APPROACH: 290 degrees & DEPART: 110 degrees. SECONDARY APPROACH: 020 degrees & DEPART: 200 degrees.  UPMC SECURITY MUST BE ON THE HELIPAD PRIOR TO DEPARTURE!!

LZ is a 2 position, 60' x 200', heated metal rooftop helipad located on top of an 11 story beige & blue colored building with the word Children's painted on it. The transient position of the helipad is painted with a white cross & red H, amber colored approach & perimeter lighting. All inbound aircraft must contact STATCom on 155.265 PL-103.5, or aviation frequency 123.05 prior to landing.
Helipad is a 2 position, 55' x 150', heated metal rooftop helipad located on top the northeastern corner of UPMC Presbyterian Hospital. The final approach and takeoff area/touchdown and liftoff area of the helipad is painted with a white cross & red H, as well as a solid white perimeter line.  There is an illuminated windsock & rotating green, white, and yellow beacon atop the elevator shaft at the end of the walkway located midpoint on the South side of the helipad. The park position is identified by the words “PARK ONLY.”  The FATO/TLOF and the Park position are separated by a taxiway identified by the words “TAXI ONLY,” and “NO PARK.”  The entire helipad incorporates appropriately colored NVG compatible perimeter/taxiway lighting.

All significant obstacles are lit with red obstacle lighting.  Direct flight over the residential area on the hillside located NNE of the pad should be avoided.

column59:
Communications (Nashville area and Vanderbilt helipads)
Notification of inbound flights shall be made to Vanderbilt Flight Communications via radio or phone 20 minutes before arrival. If you need help unloading patients, please let us know in advance.

Frequencies and Phone Numbers
Primary Radio: 122.975
Phone: (800) 288-8111

Nashville Area Advisories
1. 20 NM and 10 NM: Call with position, altitude, destination and ETA.
2. 5 NM and/or 2 minutes: Contact Flight Communications with ETA.
3. Inform Flight Communications when on final approach.
4. When departing any Nashville hospital helipad, make advisory calls and inform Flight Communication on 122.975. 

Notes
Hot off-loads (off-loading patients with rotors in motion) are not allowed without permission from the LifeFlight Communications Center.
The pilot will remain on the helipad to relocate the aircraft if it is necessary.
Wind readings from Flight Communications are not always available.
Refueling is not available for visiting aircraft.
Please review all information before arriving at Vanderbilt.

column44: Rooftop Skyport atop Vanderbilt University Medical Center.  *NOTE*  Inner Pad (marked PVT) is reserved for Vanderbilt LifeFlight Aircraft ONLY.  All other aircraft must use Outer Pad.

Communications (Nashville area and Vanderbilt helipads)
Notification of inbound flights shall be made to Vanderbilt Flight Communications via radio or phone 20 minutes before arrival. If you need help unloading patients, please let us know in advance.

Frequencies and Phone Numbers
Primary Radio: 122.975
Phone: (800) 288-8111

Nashville Area Advisories
1. 20 NM and 10 NM: Call with position, altitude, destination and ETA.
2. 5 NM and/or 2 minutes: Contact Flight Communications with ETA.
3. Inform Flight Communications when on final approach.
4. When departing any Nashville hospital helipad, make advisory calls and inform Flight Communication on 122.975. 

Hot off-loads (off-loading patients with rotors in motion) are not allowed without permission from the LifeFlight Communications Center.
The pilot will remain on the helipad to relocate the aircraft if it is necessary.
Wind readings from Flight Communications are not always available.
Skyport does have fuel service, but is reserved for Vanderbilt LifeFlight aircraft only.  Refueling is not available for visiting aircraft.
Please review all information before arriving at Vanderbilt.
